      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, why are you \"neutralizing\" `False` or empty strings by turning them into `None`? That seems like a really hacky way to handle it. If a test returns `False` every single time, it's stable. If it returns `True` then `False`, it's flaky. By turning `False` into `None`, you're actually making the logic more confusing.\n\nAlso, I tried running your logic with a test that returns `None` sometimes and `False` other times, and it's acting really unpredictable. \n\nLet's keep it simple. A test is flaky if and only if the sequence of return values is not constant. Don't try to \"neutralize\" anything. Just tell me if the outputs change across the `n_runs`. \n\nCan you rewrite it to be actually clean? No `None` conversions, no weird `if result in {\"\", None, False}` stuff. Just a straightforward check for variance in the returned values. Use my original test cases to make sure you haven't broken anything.",
